  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and treaties aimed at combating money laundering. These laws don't directly impose national laws on countries, but rather establish frameworks, standards, and cooperative mechanisms for nations to adopt and implement.  Here's a breakdown of some key international legal instruments:\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a law *per se*, the FATF is an inter-governmental body established in 1989. It sets international standards (the FATF Recommendations, also known as the \"40 Recommendations\") on combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing.  Member countries are expected to implement these recommendations in their national laws and regulations.  FATF also conducts evaluations of member countries to assess their compliance with these standards.  Countries deemed non-compliant can face various sanctions and reputational damage.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first international efforts to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking. It requires parties to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expands the criminalization of money laundering beyond drug offenses to include the proceeds of a wide range of serious crimes.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and combating money laundering related to corruption.\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and its revised version (2005):** These conventions provide a framework for European countries to cooperate in the fight against money laundering, including measures for identifying, tracing, freezing, seizing, and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n*   **International agreements and conventions on terrorist financing:** These instruments, such as the International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism, often have overlapping provisions and relevance to anti-money laundering efforts because money laundering techniques are frequently used to obscure the origins of funds intended for terrorism.\n\n**Key Features of these International Laws and Standards:**\n\n*   **Criminalization:**  Require or encourage countries to criminalize money laundering.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Call for financial institutions to implement CDD measures, including identifying and verifying customers, understanding the nature of the customer's business, and monitoring transactions.\n*   **Record Keeping:** Mandate financial institutions to keep records of transactions for a certain period.\n*   **Reporting Suspicious Transactions (STRs):**  Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to a designated Financial Intelligence Unit (FIU).\n*   **International Cooperation:** Promote cooperation among countries, including sharing information, conducting joint investigations, and providing mutual legal assistance.\n*   **Confiscation:** Aim to confiscate the proceeds of crime that are laundered.\n\n**In summary:** While no single global law directly governs money laundering in every country, a comprehensive network of international conventions, treaties, and standards (particularly those set by the FATF) shapes national laws and fosters international cooperation to combat money laundering worldwide.  Countries are encouraged, and in some cases obligated, to incorporate these international standards into their domestic legal frameworks. Failure to do so can have significant consequences.\n",
